        "confidence": 0.95,
        "insights": "The Hebrew noun \u05d0\u05b1\u05dc\u05b9\u05d4\u05b4\u0591\u05d9\u05dd (El\u014dh\u00eem) is a key term in biblical theology, derived from the root \u05d0\u05dc\u05d4 (\u02be\u0101l\u00e2), meaning 'to be strong' or 'powerful'. It appears 2570 times in the Old Testament, often translated as 'God', but its plural form (e.g., Gen 1:26) suggests a complex understanding of divinity. In ancient Near Eastern context, it could refer to multiple deities, yet in biblical monotheism, it signifies the one true God. Theologically, El\u014dh\u00eem represents the transcendent, creator God who is distinct from His creation (Isa 40:28). It also underscores God's plurality within unity, hinting at the Trinity (Gen 1:26; 11:7). Historically, it reflects a shift from polytheistic to monotheistic thought. Confidence: 0.95."
