        "confidence": 0.95,
        "insights": "The Hebrew noun \u05ea\u05b9\u05d4\u05d5\u05bc (tohu) is derived from the root verb \u05d4\u05b8\u05d9\u05b8\u05d4 (hayah), meaning 'to be' or 'to exist'. It appears 20 times in the Old Testament, primarily in Genesis and Isaiah, often paired with \u05d1\u05b9\u05d4\u05d5\u05bc (bohu), another formless state. Tohu signifies chaos, emptiness, and nothingness, echoing ancient Near Eastern creation myths where gods battle chaos monsters. In Genesis 1:2, 'the earth was without form and void; it was tohu and bohu', reflecting a primordial state awaiting divine order (bereshith). Isaiah uses tohu to describe judgment (Isa 34:11), symbolizing God's power over chaos. Theologically, tohu underscores creation ex nihilo, God's sovereignty over chaos, and the transformative power of His word (Gen 1:3). It also hints at eschatological restoration (Isa 65:17), where 'the former things' will pass away, including chaos itself."
