        "confidence": 0.95,
        "insights": "The Hebrew noun \u05e4\u05bc\u05b0\u05e0\u05b5\u05a5\u05d9 (peney), derived from the root \u05e4\u05b8\u05e0\u05b8\u05d4 (pana), meaning 'to turn' or 'face', carries profound theological significance throughout the Old Testament. Primarily denoting 'faces', it often symbolizes presence, direction, and relationship with God. In Genesis 32:30, Jacob's encounter with God results in his renaming to Israel, reflecting a transformed identity and divine presence ('I have seen God face to face'). Psalm 17:15 uses the term to express longing for God's presence in heaven, while Proverbs 29:8 warns against those who 'face' bribes. In the New Testament, John 6:40 reveals Jesus as the one who will 'see' (face) God and receive eternal life, underscoring His unique relationship with the Father. Theologically, peney signifies the human desire for divine encounter and the transformative power of God's presence."
