        "insights": "The Hebrew noun \u05d0\u05b1\u05dc\u05b9\u05d4\u05b4\u05d9\u05dd (El\u014dh\u012bm) is a plural form of the root word \u05d0\u05b5\u05dc (\u0113l), meaning 'god'. Its usage in the Tanakh reflects a complex theological evolution, from its initial polytheistic connotations to its later monotheistic interpretation. In early texts like Genesis 1:26 ('Let us make man...'), it denotes a plural council of divine beings, reflecting ancient Near Eastern polytheism. However, by the time of the prophets (e.g., Isaiah 45:5-6), El\u014dh\u012bm is clearly understood as the one true God, distinct from pagan deities. Theologically, this shift mirrors Israel's growing monotheistic consciousness. Symbolically, the plural form may hint at God's multifaceted nature or the divine council concept in ancient Near Eastern religion. Its usage also underscores the Hebraic understanding of God as a personal being who relates to humanity ('Let us make man...'). The confidence score is 0.95 due to the extensive scholarly consensus on these interpretations and the clear textual evidence supporting them."
