        "insights": "The Hebrew noun \u05dc\u05b8\u0591\u05d9\u05b0\u05dc\u05b8\u05d4 (laylah) signifies 'night' and carries profound theological significance throughout the Old Testament. In Genesis, night is created on the first day alongside light, symbolizing God's sovereignty over time and His role as the source of both illumination and rest. Psalm 74:16 uses laylah to describe God's protection during Israel's exile, highlighting His constant presence even in darkness. In Isaiah 21:11-12, night represents judgment on Babylon, illustrating God's use of laylah as a metaphor for divine retribution. Theologically, laylah underscores the duality of God's nature - He is both the giver of light and the bringer of rest, yet also the one who uses darkness to reveal His power. Its historical context ranges from creation to exile, reflecting a consistent theme of God's providence and judgment throughout Israel's history."
