        "insights": "The Hebrew noun \u05d1\u05b9\u05bc\u05e7\u05b6\u05e8 (boqer) translates to 'morning' or 'dawn', holding significant theological implications throughout the Old Testament. In Genesis 1:5, God separates light from darkness and calls the morning 'day' and the evening 'night', establishing a cosmic order that reflects His sovereignty over time and creation. Psalm 30:5 uses \u05d1\u05b9\u05bc\u05e7\u05b6\u05e8 to symbolize deliverance from distress, as the psalmist exclaims, 'Weeping may endure for a night, but joy comes in the morning.' This metaphor underscores God's faithfulness and the promise of hope after trials. In Isaiah 43:2, the prophet declares, 'When you pass through the waters, I will be with you; and through the rivers, they shall not overwhelm you; when you walk through fire, you shall not be burned, and the flame shall not consume you,' followed by 'for I am the Lord your God, the Holy One of Israel, your Savior.' Here, \u05d1\u05b9\u05bc\u05e7\u05b6\u05e8 signifies deliverance from judgment, with the morning representing a new beginning in God's presence. Theologically, \u05d1\u05b9\u05bc\u05e7\u05b6\u05e8 embodies renewal, hope, and divine intervention, echoing God's promise to bring light out of darkness (2 Corinthians 4:6)."
