        "insights": "The Hebrew noun \u05de\u05b7\u05d9\u05b4\u05dd (mayim) primarily signifies 'waters' and is rich in biblical symbolism. In Genesis, waters represent chaos before creation (Gen 1:2), echoing ancient Near Eastern cosmogonies. In the flood narrative (Gen 6-9), waters symbolize judgment and destruction, yet also redemption as Noah's ark floats on them. Psalms often use mayim to depict God's provision (Ps 36:8) or human transience (Ps 147:15-18). In Isaiah, the 'waters' of Babylon will not overwhelm Israel (Isa 43:2), while in Revelation, they represent peoples and multitudes (Rev 17:15). Theologically, mayim underscores God's sovereignty over chaos, provision in scarcity, and judgment on sin. It also foreshadows baptismal themes of death and resurrection."
