        "insights": "The Hebrew noun \u05d0\u05b1\u05dc\u05b9\u05d4\u05b4\u05d9\u05dd (El\u014dh\u00eem) is a key term in biblical theology, appearing over 2500 times in the Old Testament. It is derived from the root verb \u05d0\u05b8\u05dc\u05b7\u05d4 (\u0101lah), meaning 'to be strong' or 'powerful'. In its plural form, it often refers to the God of Israel, emphasizing His majesty and power. Historically, it was used in Canaanite culture for various deities, but in biblical monotheism, it is exclusively applied to Yahweh. Theologically, El\u014dh\u00eem signifies a transcendent, omnipotent deity who created (Gen 1:1) and sustains the universe. It also reflects God's plurality within unity, hinting at the Trinity (cf. Gen 18:2). In the context of covenantal theology, it underscores God's sovereignty and faithfulness to His promises (e.g., Gen 17:1-8). Confidence is high due to extensive scholarly consensus on these points."
